<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-invertible-matrix-theorem">
  <title>Module 2: The Invertible Matrix Theorem</title>

  <introduction>
    <objectives>
      <title>Topics and Objectives</title>
      <p>Topics: We will explore the following concepts in this video.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>the invertible matrix theorem, which is a review/synthesis of many of the concepts we have introduced</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>Objectives: Students should be able to do the following after watching this video.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>characterize the invertibility of a matrix using the Invertible Matrix Theorem</p></li>
        <li><p>construct and give examples of matrices that are/are not invertible</p></li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p><term>Equivalent Expressions</term></p>
    <blockquote cite="Baltasar Gracián">
      <p>
        <q>A synonym is a word you use when you can’t spell the other one.</q>
      </p>
      <attribution>Baltasar Gracián</attribution>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      The theorem we introduce in this section of the course gives us many ways of saying the same thing. Depending on the context, some will be more convenient than others.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-the-imt">
    <title>The Invertible Matrix Theorem</title>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-imt">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n \times n</m> matrix. These statements are all equivalent.
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol label="a">
            <li><p><m>A</m> is invertible.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>A</m> is row equivalent to <m>I_n</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>A</m> has <m>n</m> pivotal columns (all columns are pivotal).</p></li>
            <li><p><m>A\vec{x} = \vec{0}</m> has only the trivial solution.</p></li>
            <li><p>The columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent.</p></li>
            <li><p>The equation <m>A\vec{x} = \vec{b}</m> has a solution for all <m>\vec{b} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>The columns of <m>A</m> span <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>There is a <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>C</m> so that <m>CA = I_n</m> (<m>A</m> has a left inverse.)</p></li>
            <li><p>There is a <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>D</m> so that <m>AD = I_n</m> (<m>A</m> has a right inverse.)</p></li>
            <li><p><m>A^T</m> is invertible.</p></li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-imt-composition">
    <title>Invertibility and Composition</title>
    <p>
      The diagram below gives us another perspective on the role of <m>A^{-1}</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-transformation-inverse">
      <image source="w7image.png" width="60%">
        <description>Diagram showing x mapping to Ax via multiplication by A, and Ax mapping back to x via multiplication by A-inverse.</description>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The matrix inverse <m>A^{-1}</m> transforms <m>A\vec{x}</m> back to <m>\vec{x}</m>. This is because:
      <me>A^{-1}(A\vec{x}) = (A^{-1}A)\vec{x} = I\vec{x} = \vec{x}</me>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-imt-examples">
    <title>Examples</title>
    
    <exercise xml:id="ex-imt-invertible">
      <title>Example 1: Identifying Whether a Matrix is Invertible</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Is this matrix invertible?
          <me>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp -1 \amp -1 \end{pmatrix}</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Performing row operations:
          <me>
            \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp -1 \amp -1 \end{pmatrix} \sim 
            \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp -1 \amp -1 \end{pmatrix} \sim 
            \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \end{pmatrix}
          </me>
          The matrix has 3 pivot positions (one in every column). By the IMT, it is invertible.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-imt-expression">
      <title>Example 2: Constructing an Expression for the Inverse</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>A</m> is an invertible square matrix and
          <me>A^2 + 4A = I</me>
          Give an expression for <m>A^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Factoring the left side: <m>A(A + 4I) = I</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By the definition of an inverse (and items h/i of the IMT), if <m>AB=I</m> for square matrices, then <m>B=A^{-1}</m>. 
          Thus, <m>A^{-1} = A + 4I</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <summary>
    <title>The Invertible Matrix Theorem: Final Notes</title>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Items (h) and (i) of the invertible matrix theorem (IMT) lead us directly to the following theorem:
            <theorem>
              <p>If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>n \times n</m> matrices and <m>AB = I</m>, then <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are invertible, and <m>B = A^{-1}</m> and <m>A = B^{-1}</m>.</p>
            </theorem>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The IMT is a set of equivalent statements. They divide the set of all square matrices into two separate classes: invertible, and non-invertible.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            As we progress through this course, we will be able to add additional equivalent statements to the IMT (that deal with determinants, eigenvalues, etc).
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </summary>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-matrix-completion">
    <title>Example 3: Matrix Completion</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-singular-completion">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If possible, fill in the missing elements of the matrices below with numbers so that each of the matrices are <term>singular</term>. If it is not possible to do so, state why.
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol label="i">
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>A = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp \square \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}</me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>B = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp \square \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}</me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>C = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \square \end{pmatrix}</me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="i">
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Not possible.</alert> Matrix <m>A</m> is already in a form where it has three pivot positions (rows 1 and 3 already have pivots in columns 1 and 3, and row 2 has a pivot in column 2). By the IMT, it is invertible regardless of the missing entry.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Not possible.</alert> Similar to <m>A</m>, matrix <m>B</m> is upper triangular with non-zero entries on the diagonal (1, 1, 1). It will always have 3 pivots and thus be invertible.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Possible.</alert> If we let the missing entry be <m>1</m>, the second and third rows become identical (<m>0, 1, 1</m>). This makes the columns linearly dependent, so the matrix is singular.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-mcp-context">
    <title>Matrix Completion Problems (MCP)</title>
    <p>
      The previous example is a simple version of a <term>Matrix Completion Problem</term>. These are common in recitations and exams.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>The Netflix Problem</title>
      <p>
        A famous real-world MCP is the Netflix Problem. Given a ratings matrix where entry <m>(i, j)</m> is the rating of movie <m>j</m> by customer <m>i</m>, many entries are missing. The goal is to predict the missing entries to make recommendations.
      </p>
    </aside>
    
  </subsection>

  <summary>
    <title>Section Summary</title>
    <p>
      In this section, we explored:
      <ul>
        <li><p>Characterizing the invertibility of a matrix using the Invertible Matrix Theorem (IMT).</p></li>
        <li><p>Constructing and giving examples of matrices that are or are not invertible.</p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      As we progress through the course, we will continue to add more equivalent statements to the IMT.
    </p>
  </summary>
</section>